Can Riot make next year's T1 theme song MV as good as GODS? goodvibes To be honest, I think GODS this song is really touching. Rather, I don't like music that is too loud or people yelling. My ears hurt.ğŸ¥º
When it first came out, I thought it was soft because it didn't make loud noises, but I think it was right to sing it like this because the song itself was sung as if praising God, not like I was a demon god. No matter how many times I listen to it, I never get tired of it
It shows how he started as a complete underdog by taking on Blue, shows all the teams he has been through so far in Def, one by one, and the fact that he keeps failing and getting up is a complete mess in itself, and also includes a touching scene where Keria protects him in the middle and meets the enemy next time. Where can I find such a perfect epic music video?ã… ã…  Mulberry is really different from other music videos.ã… 
What really brought the narrative to life was the greatest sincerity of all time. It starts with a contrasting scene with Faker, highlighting each and every adversity that Deft has experienced, his colleagues Meiko, Doran, and Keria appear as enemies, and Keria, who is also a close personal friend, is directed with special care, and appears as a storm maid at the last moment. Faker stands in his way, but thanks to his teammates who come to help him, he overcomes it brilliantly and wins, even hugging and rejoicing... There is no real drama.

Faker god
Deft and DRX's journey and victory was just an absolute miracle. A shooting star that somehow made it through LCK playoffs, made it through Worlds play-ins, and then all the way to winning the 2022 finale. T1, after years of shortcomings, fight their way back into the LCK finals from a 7-9 standing, then winning an amazing series against KT. Despite not winning Summer, T1 came into Worlds as a completely different beast. They showed an insanely deep pool of bot champs, went deathless against C9, and completely smashed the LPL in its entirety. GODS will forever echo some of the greatest triumphs of the LCK on the international stage.

ì´ˆë°˜ë¶€ êº¼ì–µêº¼ì–µêº¼ì–µ ë‚˜ë§Œ ê·¸ë ‡ê²Œ ë“¤ë¦¼?
This video is a honourary mention to an astonishing journey of the DRX sniper, Deft. Here is how it goes: [0:09] Deft and Faker went to the same school, but only his friends know about how good Deft is; the rest only knows about Faker. [0:42] The scene depicts while Deft are still deep in trouble (he joined MVP Blue but this team only got around the lower side of the league table), Faker had achieved his first glory ever; which can be seen as Deft used Ezreal to slain the Blue Sentinel, Faker as Zed slained the Baron (Faker won the first World Championship in 2013). MVP Blue and White then got bought by Samsung, eventually became SSW and SSB. [0:58] PawN shot Deft as Jayce vs Lucian - in that respective World Championship, SSW PawN - eventually became world champions that year - had defeated SSB Deft. He left the team after the incident. [1:12] Deft joined EDG with Meiko, and in his quest of the World Championship 2015, EDG lost 0 - 3 to FNC of Rekkles in the quarterfinals. Rekkles picked Kennen in the 1st game and did so incredible that EDG tried to reuse that pick but failed miserably. [1:22] He joined KT in November 2016, and he was part of a "super team" at that time which won the LCK Summer 2018. However, in the World Championship 2018, KT lost to the eventual champions Invictus Gaming (iG) in an actually close battle from 0 - 2 to 2 - 2, and almost pulled the comeback off but the Urgot in game 5 backfired, and KT came out defeated.  [1:55] Deft joined DRX, and the scene is from the year 2020 - Keria joins from the academy with Pyosik (Mark), and the GRF duo Doran and Chovy; but DRX was battered by the eventual world champions DWG (now DK) with a score of 0 - 3 in the quarterfinals. Graves by Canyon slained Doran as Jax; Keria was seen using Braum's E to tried blocking Showmaker's Syndra's R, but failed and Deft's Senna got the hold of Syndra's E. The sad thing is, during this time - Deft lost all three knockout encounters to DK (2 - 3 in Regional Finals 2019, 0 - 3 in both LCK Summer Grand Finals and Worlds 2020 Quarterfinals).  He then joined HLE - but his LCK Spring run ended in 3rd, and the Summer one ended in 8th - but with the high coefficient they can still compete and they clinched the second seed but lost to T1 in the Regional Finals. As a result, in Worlds 2021 he had to start from Play-ins. The HLE team then got squashed by T1 in the Quarterfinals - again, with a 0 - 3 sweep.   [2:05] He left HLE but then rejoined DRX the following season (which depicts in the vid that he fell into the a deep pit but then got rescued from the DRX teammates). This time, in the World Championship 2022, he must prepare himself. The emerging elevator could be a depiction of DRX going up from the Play-ins and the Group Stage, winning the tie-breaker to advance into the QF. [2:25] He defeats Meiko (as Renata Glasc), an old teammate - indicating the reverse sweep of DRX against EDG in the quarterfinals. [2:42] Deft as Varus shot Doran's Renekton, another old teammate. DRX defeated GEN 3-1 in the semifinals to face T1. [2:50] Deft's Caitlyn got a face-off against Keria's Karma, who now plays for T1. Faker's Viktor came for the rescue, and almost killed Deft - but with Keria's Bard's E on-time,  his team came to the aid. Pyosik's Hecarim dives in first, then Kingen's Aatrox, and Deft's Caitlyn fires to finish it off. They finally won a World Championship and the dream became true.  Deft became the oldest player ever to won Worlds, and DRX became the first team ever to win it as a Play-in round participant of the respective competition.

I wish newjeans would make more songs of this concept.. it fits them so well!!!
The best underdog story. The actual story itself have layers from being this High School kid with Faker and always being under his shadow. From always succeeding but falling short of scoring a title, to watching your own teammates win it all when you are not part of it anymore and then finally when all odds are against you, you just rise up against everything by defeating this God you were always under the shadow of, securing your title that you were always denied. What I love about the music and extra layer in the video is how DRX are these band of underdogs that saved Deft and lead him to victory when all the other big teams dumped him to little bits of details like facing Meiko and Keria who not only saved him but tasted the defeat together with him, only to be against him one day. Gosh, I also love how Faker immediately came to Keria's save as this big bad considering that Keria is sort of this bratty kid that T1 loves and protect and Faker really cares about him. Just wow, the more I watch, the more details I pick up. Also it was smart to honor Rekkless from Fnatic's glory days considering the challenges he has been facing for past couple of years!

Story: Deft, the main character in this video, is well qualified to become a League of Legends professional gamer but has not been noticed by people around him. It's because there was the best professional gamer 'Faker' in the same high school. Even after Deft dropped out of high school and joined a professional gaming club, he never won a championship and did not receive much attention. No matter how hard he tried, he couldn't go beyond Faker, and he couldn't shine behind Fakers shadow. But God must be the way to shine for those who never give up. In the end, he ended up winning the trophy last year after beating Faker with a great teamwork. He have finally come out of Fakers shadow. After that, he left these words. "What's important is the unbrokable heart"

I want to be honest. Deft's story has given me a tremendous impression that is more than any other legendary story in the history of sports. But the way all our League of Legends gamers remember the beautiful legacy they created together gives me doubts. New Jeans is a K-pop singer who has debuted less than two years ago and they are not ready to make something musically memorable. They are famous, but I haven't ever been struck deeply by their songs. It's the same this time. It would be riot that have given contact out to New Jeans, but as a result, the ordinary songs of these young, good-dancing teenage girls don't bring back the feelings of that time to me. This song disappointed me.

This is the day. The day riot attached itself that is just not very good. Maybe I'm hating on it to much but this is the world's song and besides not making sense it's just awful song in my opinion with what feels like zero hype factor.
It wasn't a BAD song, it just lacked emotion and depth, a bit unremarkable... I feel like anyone really could have done this, it was a bit generic and safe. I don't know if NJ were the best pick, but clearly riot was after their fan base as they're probably the most popular at the moment. I realize it's a collaboration, but their normal music is full of character even as a casual listener, It isn't really NJ's wheelhouse and I don't blame them necessarily, it was okay... Still very happy for them and the opportunity.   After listening once I don't feel like I need to again, whereas songs like Rise you can still get chills listening years later. This felt like climbing a hill but never really reaching the peak and making it over to grandiosity. If you didn't know NJ you'd think there was only one person singing... Parts of the song were really nice but the entirety didn't quite reach what it could have in my opinion. I don't quite think NJ have the vocal prowess and color to pull out a song like this unfortunately, or maybe they weren't directed and given the chance to... I'm not sure. Either way, whether it's what I had hoped for or not doesn't matter, good for them in the end.

Deft and Faker, league of legends god players, similar life path, quite different career start, while faker won his first worlds tournament on his first try (2013), deft failed to qualify limited to just watch the matches in which faker was the big protagonist.  2014 Deft managed to qualify to the worlds tournament however his team was shattered in semi finals by their twin organization (Samsung White) team which eventually lifted the trophy that year.(Pawn appeared in the video as Deft's enemy as he had beaten him in that year)  2015 Deft and Pawn were signed by EDG from the LPL, MSI international event is held for the first time, Deft managed to lift his first international trophy in his career by defeating SKT T1 in the finals, they also qualified to wolrds tournament that year, however they were beated (0-3) in quater-finals against Fanatic with Rekkles as his enemy, 2015 year in which Faker earned his second world champion gold medal.   2016 EDG qualified to worlds, lost against ROX in quater-finals. Faker won his third world champion trophy beating ROX in the finals (event not being shown in the video)  2017 Deft was signed by KT from the LCK, didnt managed to qualify worlds, Faker was beated (0-3) in the worlds finals that year (event not being shown in the video)  2018 Deft managed to qualify to worlds tournament, they lost in quater-finals against Invictus Gaming (2-3) in one of the most intense best of five series, Invictus Gaming lifted the trophy, SKT didnt managed to qualify to the tournament. (event not being shown in the video)  2019 Deft was signed by DRX didnt manage to qualify to worlds that year, Faker lost in semi-finals against G2. (event not being shown in the video).  2020 Deft has qualified to worlds tournament this time having Keria as his Support, Keria swore to deft he will make him win the worlds championship one day nevertheless they were beaten by DWG(0-3) team which lifted the trophy that year. (event shown in the video)  2021 Deft was signed by HawnaLife Esports with Chovy as his teammate and managed to qualify, however they lost against T1 in quater-finals (0-3)  2022 Deft was transferred back to DRX managed to qualify to worlds tournament with a miracle run throughout the spring, summer, and regional tournament being always in the edge of being left behind managed to be the forth korean seed the underdogs, from play-ins to groups finishing in the top of the group, miracle reverse-sweep against EDG in quaterfinals, showing their superiority in front of GENG and finally beating T1 and Faker in the finals with the best series in the world, Keria who had swore to Deft he will make him a world champion, now as his enemy in T1 he has accomplished it, Deft had beaten the god and claims himself also as a league of legends god player

I gonna keep this as simple as possible, doesn't have the energy of a worlds anthem. The anthems of worlds are supposed to embody league, the struggles, the victory, the ability to learn and get stronger, this song just feels like the stupidest way to say "Pro players gods", it doesnt have the message the League made esports (what I think "Warriors" is supposed to embody), or the message of rising up to try to take the spot of number one (literally almost every worlds anthem, go ahead tell me I'm wrong). Worlds anthems are supposed to be tributes to those who are currently the best, and those who are rising to be the best, this song however feels like a really long and uninteresting way to say "Pro Players=Gods" or something to that effect, regardless it doesnt feel unique, or epic. Hopefully next year we'll get something good.

As someone who has followed LoL esports since 2012 this video is quite good, but misses the point of worlds. All of the previous videos showed of the previous winners and some of their trademark picks that helped them push over the line. This video however feels like a summary of worlds 2022 and a personal video for Deft.  The song also doesn't fit for worlds and I feel like riot has really lost touch with the All or Nothing songs like Rise, Take Over, Legends Never Die and more. If this song was released as a KD/A song I don't think anyone would see the difference.  I do understand that since worlds is happening in Korea they have to take in account local culture and music style, but it doesn't generate hype at all. Silver Scrapes gives more goosebumps than this disappointment of a worlds songs and I've heard Silver Scrapes for over a hundred times now.  Hope next year is better.

Animation 7/10 (Clean, but not too unique in terms of artstyle, 3D has been done by Riot Games in the past better in my opinion) Music 4/10 (Mostly sounds like premade synth patches, but it does utilize good producer practices. K/DA was better, Soul Fighter was better, etc.) Direction 6/10 (Overall, the transitions were clean but Ezreal ulting blue buff, Zed soloing baron, Sivir boomerang seemingly not returning, Senna projectile exploding - All very innacurate) VFX 9/10 (good amount of eye-candy) SFX 1/10 (Almost non-existant unless you consider strictly music)  Overall rating: 27/50 (Wouldn't make this an anthem for worlds, maybe use it for a forgettable event instead) Keep in mind that this is my SUBJECTIVE opinion and if you don't agree that's completely fine. We have all seen better Worlds anthems and better trailers overall so COMPARED to them it's a bit underwhelming.

The detail they put into this story is insane. Scene context for newer players as a huge Deft fan:  1.	â Deft sees Faker at school (they went to the same high school) and starts grinding league at home after he sees Faker pop off on his signature Zed in season 3. 2.	â Deft's meteoric rise on SSB, becomes famous for his Ez and Lucian and comes into Worlds 2014 as the #1 seed from Korea. Gets knocked out of Worlds by SSB and *PaWn's famous Jayce. 3.	â Deft moves to EDG as part of the first Korean exodus to LPL. He wins MSI with Meiko on Thresh, but famously gets 3-0'd against Fnatic and Rekkles' AD Kennen at Worlds. 4.	â Fast forward to 2020, and Deft is on his hyperscaling Senna alongside Doran on his Jax as part of DRX, back in the LCK. Damwon's Showmaker (Syndra) and Canyon (Graves) are by far the best players in the world, and they destroy Deft's dreams of winning worlds again despite Keria's best efforts on Braum to protect him. 5.	â Deft sinks into a dark place as Korean and international netizens alike question his ability to win + clutch factor etc. Is he washed? Not shown are the many years on KT/EDG in between that Deft frequently came into Worlds as the #1 seed and his team underperformed, or missed the tournament entirely. Just as it seems he may never resurface, he's pulled out of the depths by the DRX miracle run roster of last year, who go on a crazy gauntlet run just to make worlds. Starting from LCK regionals on, they are the underdog in almost every Bo5 they play. 6.	â Worlds 2022 starts, and Deft is forced to confront all of his old teammates one by one in order to rise to the top. This starts with his previous lanemate Meiko on Renata. Deft demonstrates a new level of skill and ability this year, pulling out the Draven to dispatch EDG Meiko (and Viper!!) and then the Varus to beat Doran's Renekton, who is now on Gen G (and Chovy!!). Finally, he comes face to face with his old friend Keria, and his new team T1 in World finals. Just as his Caitlyn seems to have Keria's Karma in his sights, Faker appears on his feared Viktor to seemingly dash Deft's hopes once again. But Deft is no longer alone and the only star player on his team. The DRX roster teleports in, and Zeka's Azir sets up Deft to fire the final headshot at T1, winning the championship and lifting the Worlds Trophy after 10 long years.  Legendary. The video closes with various Worlds players this year eyeing the trophy, and glory, once again.  (Credit to /u/DoubleBieber from the Reddit thread)
Haven't seen anyone else comment on it, so I guess I will. Scrolling through the comments section, I see posts in at least half a dozen languages from all across the planet. I've never seen such a diverse comment section on a Youtube video; not sure if it's a change on Youtube's end or Riot's, but it's awesome to see the global LoL community brought together like this for Worlds!

I have to say I do like the visuals, the lyrics and vocals. If I had to criticise something, it would be two minor things: To many players looked to similar. Maybe it's because I am only a casual Esports fan, but more distinctions would have been nice. I was like "is this faker?"Every time someone with glasses was shown. My last criticism would have been that, for me, the refrain didn't mix well with the rest of the song. When I heard the first "Go, go, go, god" part, it felt like a theme for a final boss or some sort, while the rest of the text was more for an MC. The final "go go go", on the other hand, was well mixed with the rest of the theme.

its all about deft
Alright so I don't comment often on Riot works because I'm mostly super happy with their art direction. But this time, man, I HAVE to compare this year's anthem with the previous ones. It has to be the most boring, least dynamic cinematic I've seen since the summoner's rift unreal engine disaster... Why is there so little details in the backgrounds ? So little details on the characters ? why is every action slowed down or cut before the impact frame ? The scenario of the cinematic is mostly the same as 2018's Rise and oh man, do I even have to compare the two ?  The song is also a bit forgettable but I will listen to it until I like it anyway, like every years haha Anyway, just a little rent. I'm just hoping every year for another masterpiece ( because we all know Riot is CAPABLE of doing insane things ) but it never comes. How disapointing. WE WANT MORE RIOT, we shouldn't be disapointed by you. Please don't let us down like the Pokemon franchise did.

god
Genuinely amazed. My jaw literally dropped from the opening few seconds and I think it's because it's like two worlds merging into one for me (kpop and a decade of League of Legends music). I know we've had K/DA with G(I)-DLE's Soyeon and Miyeon before, but that felt more like a collaboration between two different styles (which was great, btw): western YouTube artists and Korean kpop.  With this song, it's got that classic American League of Legends Worlds music style from the (electronic?) beat to the diction, but you can recognize it's coming from the voices of the NewJeans girls (it's hard to understate how famous and mainstream they've become this past year in Korea)... mind-blowing.

newjeans cooked for worlds
Feels like a decent anthem, though a little repetitive. a worse song than Star Walking, but a better Anthem. It has the nice drop and easy lyrics for people to sing along with, yet lacks a bit of punch so it doesn't hit as hard.  Much love to artists who worked on it as I'm sure they've poured so much into it with what they got... but-,  it seems lower quality than past anthem animations, not a fan of the almost plastic-like 3D style as it tend to make the people feel soulless. Animations that blend techniques are so much better, Arcane has been praised so highly because of it, we've seen quality from Riot published works, shame this does not look like one of them.  It's like they're moving resources away from League of Legends, and putting it into Valorant and other projects. Ticking Away, is (in my opinion) the better anthem we got this year. Both in the music and art department.

I'm obviously not the target market for this video. I'm a big KDA and Arcane fan. I'm not much of a gamer but I'm looking forward to the fighting game. So... I didn't know any of these guys.  The animation wasn't at all bad, but it also wasn't close to your best. Even though I usually pay to download your World's anthems because they bop... this one didn't do anything for me lyric-wise. Kinda felt like it was missing the 'cleverness' you guys usually bring to production. And this one almost felt like a remix of one of your previous anthems instead of something new.  I recommend you go orchestral or the other direction to electric guitar next time, I think you can make something epic that doesn't sound so similar to the last several pop anthems you've put out.

I notice a few comments saying â€œwhy are only Koreans are featuredâ€ or â€œthis is meant to be a world video where are the western teamsâ€. The reason is  because music video is actually about Deftâ€™s journey working with PAST teammates, which from 2:22 onwards he eventually had to face in the final stages of worlds 2022 - on a different team. Since he was mostly involved with Asian teams it's hard to feature many Western teams (apart from FNC Rekkles at 1:15).  Some key moments: 0:55 - SSB Pawn - SSW Deft lost to Former team member in Worlds 2014 2:25 - EDG Meiko - former team member at 1:07 in EDG 2015  2:38 - GenG Doran - former team member at 1:30 in DRX 2020  2:50 - SKT1 Keria - former team member at 1:44 in DRX 2020

ì´ê±° ê³µì‹ ì£¼ì œê°€ì„?ë³„ë¡œë„¤
Epic Journey of Deft to lift the trophy with DRX last year. You can see as it starts with him attending highschool with faker, true story btw it was Mapo High School at Gangseo-gu Seoul. Then we can see Faker in season 3 as Zed where lifted his first trophy and looking at Deft from above. Faker gets his first shot with SSG blue and he lost to SSG white as we can see them fighting as Lucian vs Jayce SSW Pawn. Then we see him fighting Rekkles as signature pick Kennen adc with Meiko on Thresh on Worlds 2015 quarter finals. We can then see his return playing Senna at Worlds 2020 in the segment with DRX Doran (Jax) and DRX Keria (Braum) vs DWG Canyon (Graves) and DWG ShowMaker (Syndra) as they got knocked out 3-0 by the future champions. Next we got The 2022 DRX roster picking him up for an ultimate attempt. He appears as Draven vs Meiko's Renata in the quarterfinals against his former team EDG. Then in the semifinals he fought GenG Doran's Renekton with his Varus. And finally the finals segment he shows up as Caitlyn versus his old highschool friend the Demon King Faker on Viktor and his old teammate Keria on Karma. He gets knocked out by Faker when his whole team appears through Beryl's Bard portal (Kingen's Aatrox, Pyosik's Hecarim, Zeka's Azir and Beryl's Bard) to pick him up and seal the championship in that epic rollercoster of game 5 we've all watched. He finally gets crowned World Champion after so many years of trying. A true underdog story, the story of Deft and DRX. I think they should have also emphasized more on the story of DRX's fight through regional qualifiers in Korea, Worlds play-ins and getting to the top when nobody believed in them not even the slightest. The video ends as many more underdogs watch the story unfold and dream of doing the same, featuring: Hans Sama, Berserker, Yutapon, Chovy (he is the odd one in that segment), Yazhu, Ayu.. etc
Wow
I didn't need any more reasons to love NewJeans but here we are.
Amazing animation and song, as always XD

í•´ì²´ê¹Œì§€ ë³„ ë‹¤ì„¯ê°œ ë‚˜ëˆ ì§€ëŠ”ê±° ë‚˜ì™”ìœ¼ë©´ í¼í™íŠ¸
Videoclip explanation and every match reference: 0:00 At the beginning we can see Deft at school with Faker, both attended Mapo High School and in an interview Deft said that Faker was really famous there. We can conclude that the 0:15 to 0:55 part represents how being "Faker's shadow" inspired him to win worlds some day.  0:56 Worlds 2014 semifinals SSB vs SSW, in game 2 Deft played Lucian against Pawn's Jayce, lost the game and the series. 1:10 Worlds 2015 quarterfinals EDG vs FNC, Rekkles picked kennen and Meiko picked thresh in game 1 and Deft picked sivir in game 3, lost both games and the series. 1:30 Worlds 2020 quarterfinals DRX vs DWG,  Showmaker picked Syndra in the first game, in the second game Deft, Doran and Canyon picked Senna, Jax and graves respectively, while Keria picked Braun in the third one. DRX lost the three games and the series ended 3-0. 1:40 I think this scene represents the fact that Keria at the moment was Deft's support and promised to him that he would help him win worlds. Little did he know that they would meet at a Worlds final two years later. 2:00 After 6 worlds appearances and 0 titles,  Deft's dream of being a world champion started to fade. Rumours of his retirement began to circulate, lamenting that one of the greatest players in LoL history would end his career without a Worlds trophy. 2:12 Deft saw the light at the end of the tunnel coming back to DRX again, now with new teammates, regaining hope once again. The last dance. After a mediocre LCK year, DRX roughly classified to Worlds, starting at play-in. 2:23 Worlds 2022 quarterfinals DRX vs EDG game 3, DRX was down 2-0, when Deft played Draven against his former teammate Meiko, who picked Renata. They won this map and reverse sweeped the series. 2:36 Worlds 2022 semifinals DRX vs GENG game 4, DRX was winning the series 2-1, and in this game Deft had a great performance with varus against his ex-teammate Doran, who picked Renekton. They ended up winning the game and the series. 2:48 Worlds 2022 finals DRX vs T1 game 5, after 4 spectacular games, silver scrapes started to play in the arena. Deft was one step away to achieve his dream, but to do that he would have to defeat his former teammate and his friend, Keria, who played Karma, and the person who overshadowed him in high school, the greatest of all time, Faker, who picked Viktor. But he wasn't alone, his team was there to help him beat them and become a world champion in the end. 3:25 After winning Worlds, Kingen (Aatrox), Pyosik (Hecarim), Zeka (Azir), Deft (Caitlyn) and Beryl (Bard) finally became GODS. At the end we can see some players from different regions, in most cases legends of their region. 3:43 G2 Hans Sama is the one looking at the camera, the other one is FURIA Ayu, a brazilian player. 3:46 The one with the cap is C9 Blaber, the other one is EST Josedeodo, an argentinian player (his hair doesn't match but his jacket says JOSEDEODO). 3:48 From left to right, GAM Levi (Vietnam), DFM Yutapon (Japan), PSG Azhi (Taiwan). 3:51 In this frame there are 9 players, I don't know who the other ones are.

New theme is pretty good tbh. NewJeans did their part pretty well imho.     But that isnt the problem here. The VIDEO itself is the problem. League is undeniably the MOST popular game in Korea every single League player is very popular at school yes even wayyy back in the 2013s. Kids in Korean schools especially WILL be talking about League all day everyday so the scene of Deft being ignored is highly unlikely, as he has never been the autistic kid sitting in the back like in an average western school because League players are literal GODS and high ranked dudes are treated like celebrities even when they dont say a word.  So taking the Western perspective to a Korean school about an ignored nerdy kid playing video games is kinda a BIG problem, as this isnt how it works in the East. Irdk dont know why they didnt bother doing research but the script is very mehhh and a big turndown of an otherwise decent music video.

There's one thing I absolutely hate with Riot & worlds songs.   Recently they haven't been as hype as they used to be. Worlds is all about creating hype for the action that'll take place.   But lately with Phoenix (sounds like a pop single), Take Over (Chill rap song?) Star Walking (random, chill pop song?) and Burn It Down was decent, but still lacked a definitve build up. The preview of Gods sounded real nice, just hope it won't be riddled with traces of Kpop. This is worlds after all, keep it on brand. There's a reason why most people regard Warriors, RISE etc. as the best ones.
